[Dashboard Widget Failure Investigation > 3. Root Cause Chain > Bug #1 (Primary) — DuckDB-WASM disabled for automated browsers]

A DevRev **frontend deployment** introduced automation detection. The JavaScript code checks `navigator.webdriver` before initializing DuckDB-WASM:

```javascript
// Simplified representation of what the DevRev app does:
if (navigator.webdriver) {
  // Automation detected — skip DuckDB, use server-side query
  fetchFromServer(sql); // → calls oasis.data.query
} else {
  // Normal user — use DuckDB-WASM
  initDuckDB().then(() => runQuery(sql));
}
```

Playwright Test **always sets `navigator.webdriver = true`** as part of its browser automation protocol (Chrome DevTools Protocol / CDP). This is a standard browser automation marker. Because of this, every Playwright-automated browser session is detected and routes to the server-side fallback.

[Dashboard Widget Failure Investigation > 6. The Solution > Two-Part Fix > Part 1: `playwright.config.ts` — Disable Chrome's automation advertisement]

```typescript
launchOptions: {
  args: [
    ...(process.env.CI ? ['--no-sandbox'] : []),
    // Prevents Chrome from advertising itself as automation-controlled.
    // Without this, the DevRev app detects navigator.webdriver=true and
    // disables DuckDB-WASM, falling back to oasis.data.query which returns
    // 500 in preprod-jp — causing all dashboard widgets to fail.
    '--disable-blink-features=AutomationControlled',
  ],
},
```

The `--disable-blink-features=AutomationControlled` flag tells Chrome not to set the `AutomationControlled` Blink feature flag. This is the browser-process-level suppression of automation advertisement.

[Dashboard Widget Failure Investigation > 6. The Solution > Two-Part Fix > Part 2: `src/fixtures/page.fixtures.ts` — Mask `navigator.webdriver` before page scripts run]

```typescript
page: async ({ page }, use) => {
  // Mask navigator.webdriver before any page scripts run.
  // The DevRev app checks this property to detect automation and disables
  // DuckDB-WASM when true, routing to a broken server-side fallback instead.
  // Setting it to undefined restores the normal user code path (DuckDB-WASM).
  await page.addInitScript(() => {
    Object.defineProperty(navigator, 'webdriver', { get: () => undefined });
  });
  await dismissPromotionalBanners(page);
  await use(page);
},
```

Even with `--disable-blink-features=AutomationControlled`, Playwright injects `navigator.webdriver = true` at the JavaScript level via CDP. The `addInitScript` call runs **before any page JavaScript executes** and overrides the property getter to return `undefined`. This makes the browser indistinguishable from a regular user session from the app's perspective.

Both parts are needed because they operate at different layers:
- The Chrome flag handles the browser-process level
- The init script handles the JavaScript/DOM level

